[[File:JPods Traffic Choice Colors.jpg|thumb|Illustration of JPods network]]

'''JPods''' is a [[personal rapid transit]] concept which uses distributed collaborative computer networks to route transit in a manner similar to the data trafficking of the Internet. Developed by JPods, Inc, the vehicles consist of ultra-light pods controlled by on-board computers.

Personal rapid transit was defined in Congressional Office of Technology Assessment Study ''PB-244854''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpods.com/JPods/003LastOilCrisis/7503_LastOilCrisis.PDF |title=PB-244854 |publisher=Congressional Office of Technology Assessment |date= |accessdate=1975-06-01}}</ref>  as the solution for urban transport in response to the [[1973 oil embargo|1973 Oil Embargo]].  [[Morgantown, West Virginia]] installed a PRT system that has delivered 110&nbsp;million oil-free, injury-free [[passenger miles]]{{cn|date=June 2015}}, but where huge budget overruns crippled interest in PRT for several decades.

== Transport Characteristics ==
In the demonstration JPod, people get in, select a destination on a touch screen and the vehicle navigates to that address.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bh3yYAShTjA |title=Fox 9 News |publisher=Fox 9 News |date= | accessdate= 2006-11-15}}</ref>  In production models people and/or cargo will set destination and travel non-stop from origin to destination.

== Installations ==
[[File:Secaucus Letter of Intent.jpg|thumb|Letter of Intent between JPods, Inc and the Town of Secaucus, NJ to build a JPods Network.]]
[[File:Time-Map of Secaucus, NJ.jpg|thumb|Time map illustrating walking, ticketing, and travel time from the Blue Cross. Green is 10 minutes, Yellow is 20 minutes, and Red is 30 minutes.]]

JPods has signed [[letters-of-intent]] (see image of letter to the right) to build networks in 2014 with the cities of [[Secaucus, New Jersey|Secaucus]] ({{convert|5|mi|abbr=out|adj=on}} network, US-NJ), [[Anshan]] ({{convert|30|km|order=flip|abbr=out|adj=on}}, China), and [[Linyi]] ({{convert|200|km|adj=on|order=flip|abbr=out}}, China). On June 25, 2014 the Town of Secaucus passed a Performance Standards Ordinance making it a law to grant rights of way access based on exceeding 120 passenger-miles per gallon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vimeo.com/102592696 |title=Ordinance 2014-23, Performance Standards |publisher=Town of Secaucus, NJ |date= | accessdate= 2014-06-24}}</ref>

== System details ==
* vehicles weigh approximately {{convert|500|lb}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solarevolution.com/PRT/jpods/energyNeutralTransportation.htm |title=Energy Neutral Transportation |publisher=Solarevolution.com |date= |accessdate=2014-02-16}}</ref> with a gross carrying capacity of {{convert|1700|lb}}{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}
* vehicles travel suspended below an overhead guideway that encases the bogies
* bogies are the mechanisms that propel vehicles and from which the vehicle chassis is suspended. Bogies are composed of generally of motors, controllers, wheels, gearboxes, sensors, and switches.
* switch control is managed by the vehicle and/or by the network
* solar powered<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earthtoys.com/emagazine.php?issue_number=07.06.01&article=ingenuity |title=Alternative Energy eMagazine - &#124; AltEnergyMag |publisher=Earthtoys.com |date= |accessdate=2014-02-16}}</ref>
* travel between {{convert|30|and|40|mph|abbr=out}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alternative-energy-news.info/jpod-transportation-concept/ |title=JPod Transportation Concept |publisher=Alternative-energy-news.info |date=2007-01-04 |accessdate=2014-02-16}}</ref>

The computer network is managed in three tiers:
* devices such as pods, switches, structures
* negotiators collaborate with devices and load managers to set routes
* load managers log time based demand to create a terrain map that allow appropriate routes to be identified and scheduled

