A '''jobber''', or [[petroleum]] marketer, is a person or company that purchases quantities of refined fuel from refining companies (e.g. [[BP]], [[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell]], [[Exxon]]), either for sale to retailers (e.g., [[Filling station|gasoline stations]]), or to sell directly to the users of those products (e.g., home [[heating oil]] to homeowners, lubricating oils to industrial operations or repair shops, [[jet fuel]] to [[Fixed base operator|FBO]]s, etc.). In essence, the jobber acts as the "middleman" between the company that refines the petroleum products and those that either use them or market them at retail prices.{{fact|date=July 2015}}  The jobber often owns the gasoline being sold, and the station it is being sold to, but allows an operator to lease the store.{{fact|date=July 2015}}

In 2001, 44.3% of all gasoline in the U.S. was sold through jobbers.{{fact|date=July 2015}}  Approximately the same percentage was sold through integrated oil company owned and operated stores or franchise arrangements. The percentage of jobbers responsible for fuel sale in the USA in 2004 fell to 37.3%.{{fact|date=July 2015}}

Jobbers are represented by trade associations such as the Association for Convenience & Fuel Retailing, National Association of Shell Marketers, Sigma: America's Leading Fuel Marketers, and the Petroleum Marketers Association of America.

