The '''Reclaimed Wood Council''' was a [[trade association]] that promoted [[reclaimed wood]] from old buildings or from logs reclaimed from rivers. The Council was formed in May 2003 and dissolved in January 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heartpine.com/pdf/ReclaimedWoodsOverview.pdf |title= Virgin-growth, old-growth, original-growth, antique or aged… (Reclaimed Wood Council definitions)|publisher=Goodwin Heart Pine Company}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YTExAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BXIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6722,862596&dq=reclaimed-wood-council&hl=en |title=Reclaimed Wood Steps Up For Floors |date=November 13, 2004 |work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |accessdate=June 6, 2012 |quote=While the Reclaimed Wood Council, a national trade group, is working to establish standards for antique heart pine and other woods, to date there are no ...}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news |url = http://timesfreepress.com/news/2008/oct/02/georgia-recycled-wood-industry-gains-polish-confid/ |title = Georgia: Recycled wood industry gains polish, confidence |first = Amy |last = Williams |newspaper = Chattanooga Times Free Press |date = October 2, 2008 |quote = ... according to the Reclaimed Wood Council, a group formed by industry members to ensure uniform standards of salvaged and reclaimed wood products. |accessdate = June 6, 2012 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://archive.is/20130204190557/http://timesfreepress.com/news/2008/oct/02/georgia-recycled-wood-industry-gains-polish-confid/ |archivedate = February 4, 2013 |df = }}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heartpine.com/pdf/hardwood_floors_magazine_august_2002.pdf |title= Antique Shopping |publisher=Hardwood Floors Magazine |date=August 2002 }}</ref>
