The '''stick''' may refer to several separate units, depending on the item being measured. {{TOC limit|2}} {{anchor|Type|Typography}} ==Length== In [[typography]], the stick, '''stickful''',{{sfn|Jackson|1937|loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=YYuaAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA70 p.&nbsp;70]}}{{sfnp|Pasko|1894}} or {{nowrap|'''stick of type'''}}{{sfnp|Williamson|1984|p=xliii}} was an inexact length based on the size of the various [[composing stick]]s used by [[newspaper]] [[editing|editors]] to assemble pieces of [[moveable type]]. In English-language papers, it was roughly equal to 2 [[column inch]]es or 100–150 words.{{sfnp|Williamson|1984|p=xliii}} In [[France]], [[Spain]], and [[Italy]], sticks generally contained only between 1 and 4 lines of text each.{{sfnp|Pasko|1894}} A [[Column (typography)|column]] was notionally equal to 10 sticks.{{sfnp|OED|1916}}{{sfnp|Campbell-Copeland|1893|loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=v3nYwTJDPwkC&pg=PA39 p.&nbsp;39]}}
{{anchor|Butter}} ==Mass== In [[American cooking]], a {{nowrap|'''stick of [[butter]]'''}} is taken to be 4 [[ounce]]s{{sfnp|Bloom|2007|loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=cyR9VsqMvJsC&pg=PA31 p.&nbsp;31]}} (about 113&nbsp;[[gram (unit)|g]]).{{sfnp|Butter Baking|2015}}
==Volume== In [[American cooking]], a stick of [[butter]] may also be understood as ½&nbsp;[[cup (unit)|cup]] or 8&nbsp;[[tablespoon]]s{{sfnp|Bloom|2007|loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=cyR9VsqMvJsC&pg=PA31 p.&nbsp;31]}} (about 125&nbsp;[[milliliters|mL]]).{{sfnp|Butter Baking|2015}}
